{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d468dc2-bdbe-4e7f-98db-7e34eb419d53","content":"To switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, make these changes in your project file:\n\n1. **Remove** (or set to `false`) the VSTest opt-in:\n   ```xml\n   <!-- Delete this line -->\n   <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n   ```\n\n2. That's it for `MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0` — Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the **default** runner. `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was opting you *out* of it. Removing it opts you back in.\n\n**Key behavioral differences to expect:**\n\n- **CLI output** – tests produce console output directly (no need for `dotnet test --logger`).\n- **Running tests** – `dotnet test` still works, but you can also run the test executable directly (`./MyTests.exe`).\n- **Extensions** – VSTest adapters (`.runsettings`-based) are replaced by Microsoft.Testing.Platform extensions. If you use `.runsettings`, check which settings still apply.\n- **CI** – if your CI depends on `--logger trx`, add the NuGet package `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` and pass `--report-trx` instead.\n\n**Verify** after the change:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test\n```\n\nIf anything breaks, check for VSTest-specific adapters or loggers in your project and replace them with their Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c58fdb00-0c73-4297-aa9f-2874b1edeace","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"5C31:196AFA:A801A:D38C7:69F54B31"},"id":"1cb57d88-9ff8-455b-a773-14cb4273fd33","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:54:19.885Z","parentId":"d047a7d0-cb51-49ed-bdd9-0f9e25f69bf7"}
